														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-952729">
									

<p>It's true that, by definition, "malevolent" means "bearing ill will", and a non-sapient idea (or restaurant) can't very well have any kind of will. I'd argue that in the Keter definition, though, "malevolent" is slightly metaphorical and could easily be replaced with "actively dangerous". Nonsapient objects that nonetheless actively seek to do harm fit the sense of the thing. Think of a heat-seeking missile. It is in no way sapient, or even sentient, but once it's fired it takes direct action to do harm.</p>
<p>In short, yes, this is in some sense actively malevolent and definitely Keter. Chubert, may I edit the class to reflect that?</p>

